 for bestpractices and # 404 Not Found

## Overview
Create a user-friendly 404 Not Found page to be shown whenever a navigation target does not exist or cannot be resolved. The page should feel consistent with the Gbox360 design system: calm, professional, informative, and action-oriented. It must gracefully guide users back to productive parts of the app (dashboard/landing) and offer quick recovery actions (search fallback). The implementation must be robust against null/undefined values, guard all array operations, and follow the project’s runtime safety standards.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- A dedicated 404 Not Found page that presents a friendly, human-centric error state when a user attempts to access a non-existent route or resource.

Goals:
- Immediately communicate that the page isn’t found without causing user frustration.
- Reassure users and provide clear, fast recovery options: go to Dashboard, go to Landing, or search for a target.
- Maintain visual consistency with Gbox360’s design language, typography, spacing, and color system.
- Include an accessible search box to help users locate a valid target quickly.
- Include primary navigation cues to return to safe ground (home/dashboard) and a minimal, elegant error explanation.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Hero/Headline: Large, bold H1 stating the page isn’t found (e.g., “Oops — Page not found” or “404: We can’t seem to find that page”).
- Subtext: Brief apology and guidance (e.g., “The page you’re looking for doesn’t exist or has moved. Let’s get you back on track.”).
- Search Box: Prominent search input with clear placeholder (e.g., “Search for a company, report, or topic…”), a search icon, and a rounded outline. Include an accessible, keyboard-friendly submission with Enter.
- CTAs:
  - Primary: Go to Dashboard (filled, dark navy background).
  - Secondary: Go to Landing (outlined, subtle border).
- Quick navigation:
  - Home or Dashboard link in the header area as a fallback.
  - Optional “Recently viewed” or “Popular links” chips/cards if space allows (not required).
- Visual guidance:
  - Subtle illustration or neutral iconography representing navigation error, kept minimal to align with enterprise aesthetic.
- Accessibility:
  - High-contrast text, proper aria-labels, and focus-visible states. Keyboard navigable.

Visual guidance:
- Use the project’s color palette and typography tokens to align with the rest of the app.
- Maintain generous whitespace, and center the hero content aesthetically within the page.
- Maintain consistent card and surface treatments for any helper panels or suggestions.

## Components to Build
- 404PageContainer
  - Props: none (uses app routing)
  - Layout: centered content block with responsive padding.
  - Subcomponents:
    - HeroHeadline
    - Subtext
    - SearchBox
    - ActionButtons (Primary and Secondary CTAs)
    - Optional QuickLinks (array-driven, guarded rendering)
- SearchBox
  - Input handling with onSubmit callback
  - Placeholder text
  - Clear error/empty states
  - Accessibility: aria-label, role="search"
  - Guard all input values against null/undefined
- CTAButton
  - Reusable button component for primary/secondary actions
  - Props: variant (primary/secondary), label, onClick
  - Accessible focus states and keyboard interaction
- HeaderNav (if not already present on 404)
  - Minimal presence or reuse existing header with home/dashboard link

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Routing:
  - Configure app routing to render 404Page for unknown paths (catch-all route) and ensure it does not crash if route props are missing.
- UI Components:
  - 404PageContainer: responsive, accessible, and aligned with typography scale.
  - SearchBox: controlled component with value state initialized to "" (useState<string>(“”)).
  - CTAButton: accessible button styling, with proper focus rings and hover/active states.
- State and safety:
  - Guard array and data usage: if any list of quick links is rendered, ensure (links ?? []).map(...) with Array.isArray checks.
  - Do not assume any data from API; if data is fetched in future, use const items = Array.isArray(data?.items) ? data.items : [] and safe map calls.
- Styling:
  - Implement using the project’s design tokens for colors, typography, radii, and shadows.
  - Card/surface treatment should match the style: white surfaces, subtle borders (#E5E7EB), soft shadows.
- Accessibility:
  - Ensure sufficient color contrast (WCAG AA) for text and CTAs.
  - Focus ring visible on keyboard navigation; use the prescribed focus color (#93C5FD) for focus outlines.
- Performance:
  - Lightweight page with minimal JS payload; no heavy assets; lazy-load any optional assets.

### Backend
- Not required for this MVP since the page is static-based. If the project uses a CMS or dynamic content for suggestions, ensure endpoints are optional and guarded, returning [] when not available.

### Integration
- Ensure the 404 page is wired into the router as a catch-all fallback.
- Ensure header/navigation remains consistent, with a home/dashboard shortcut visible so users can recover quickly.
- If there is a global 404 layout, reuse it to maintain consistency across routes.

## User Experience Flow
- User navigates to a non-existent route.
- System renders the 404 Not Found page:
  - Centered hero headline appears with supportive subtext.
  - A prominent search box invites the user to search for a valid target.
  - Primary CTA redirects to the Dashboard; secondary CTA returns to the Landing or Home.
  - Optional quick links or recent items may render if available.
- User interacts with the search box:
  - Enters a query and submits via Enter or click on a search icon.
  - If the app supports search handling on the 404 page, perform a query; otherwise, suggest navigating to Dashboard or Landing.
- User can click CTAs to recover navigation to a safe starting point.

## Technical Specifications
- Data Models: None required for static 404 page. If implementing quick links:
  - Schema: QuickLink { id: string, label: string, href: string }
  - Retrieval: const links = Array.isArray(data?.links) ? data.links : []
- API Endpoints: None required for MVP. If future, endpoints should be protected and return [] when unavailable.
- Security: No authentication required for 404 page. Ensure there is no sensitive data leakage.
- Validation:
  - Input validation for the search box: trim whitespace, prevent empty submissions, handle null/undefined gracefully.
  - Use data ?? [] when consuming external results (if any).
- State defaults:
  - useState<string>("") for search input.
  - useState<QuickLink[]>([]) for optional quick links.

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] The 404 page renders correctly on unknown routes without crashing, with a responsive, accessible layout that mirrors the design system.
- [ ] The page includes a prominent search box with accessible label, placeholder, and proper submission behavior.
- [ ] Primary CTA navigates to the Dashboard; Secondary CTA navigates to Landing/Home. Both buttons are keyboard accessible and visually aligned with the design tokens.
- [ ] All array operations in the page code guard against null/undefined by using (items ?? []) or Array.isArray checks, and useState initializations for arrays to [].
- [ ] If optional quick links are rendered, they use safe guards: Array.isArray(links) ? links.map(...) : [].
- [ ] Visuals adhere to the specified color palette, typography, and spacing, with proper focus rings and high contrast.

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Follow the 12-column responsive grid, generous vertical rhythm, and left-aligned text blocks.
- Center the hero content; ensure consistent baseline alignment with header elements.
- Use a clean card-less surface for the 404 page, with an optional minimal illustration kept within the card/surface language.
- Maintain enterprise-grade polish: subtle shadows, borders, and precise spacing.
- Prioritize fast scannability and clear CTAs; provide an intuitive recovery path to the Dashboard or Landing.

## Visual Style

### Color Palette:
- Primary background: #FBFBFC
- Map/background overlay: #F3F4F6
- Primary text: #111827
- Secondary text / meta: #6B7280
- Borders / dividers: #E5E7EB
- Card background / surfaces: #FFFFFF
- Accent (callouts / badges): #FF6B4A
- Accent (interactive / primary CTA): #0F172A
- Accent (focus / subtle highlights): #93C5FD
- Muted success/credibility accent: #10B981

### Typography & Layout:
- Font family: Inter / SF Pro / system-ui
- Hierarchy:
  - H1: 48–56px, weight 700
  - H2: 24–32px, weight 600–700
  - Body: 16px, weight 400, line-height 1.4–1.6
  - Micro/metadata: 12–14px, weight 500/400
  - Numeric stats: 28–36px, weight 700
- Spacing & grid:
  - Centered container with wide gutters; 12-column grid
  - 48–64px vertical rhythm between major sections
  - Card padding: 20–28px; controls padding: 12–16px
  - Alignment: left-aligned text; center hero; consistent baseline
- Typography treatments: bold numerals for metrics when used; restrained caps for metadata

### Key Design Elements
- Card Design: white surfaces, 1px borders, soft drop shadows, 10–12px border radius
- Navigation: top bar, active states with subtle accent, pill-shaped CTAs
- Data Visualization: not required for 404, but if included, keep minimal and single-tone
- Interactive Elements: accessible buttons, inputs with focus states, graceful hover transitions
- Micro-interactions: 150–220ms hovers, 300ms panel transitions if used
- Accessibility: high contrast, visible focus rings, keyboard navigable

### Design Philosophy
- Modern, trust-focused minimalism
- Clean, corporate aesthetic with restrained color accents
- Spatial calm and hierarchy with ample whitespace
- Transparent UI cues to communicate helpful recovery

API integrations:
- No APIs connected for MVP.

